==English==

===Etymology===
From {{L.}} ''rhinoceros'', ''[[rhinocerontas]]'', from {{Gr.}} [[ῥις]] (rhis) nose, + [[κέρας]] (keras) horn

===Pronunciation===
*(''[[RP]]''): /raɪˈnɒsərəs/, /<tt>raI"nQs@r@s</tt>/
*(''US''): rī-näsʹərəs, /raɪˈnɑːsərəs/, /<tt>raI"nA:s@r@s</tt>/
*{{audio|en-us-rhinoceros.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|sg=rhinoceros|pl='''rhinoceros''', '''[[rhinoceroses]]''' or, in Britain, '''[[rhinocerotes]]'''}}

# Any of several large [[herbivorous]] [[pachyderm]]s native to Africa and Asia of the family [[Rhinocerotidae]], with thick, gray skin and one or two [[horn]]s on their [[snout]]s. Short form: '''[[rhino]]'''

====Usage notes====
{{unreferenced}}
*In natural history, the plural ''rhinoceros'' is often used, in the same way that the singular of the names of many wild animals is often used in natural history as the plural (compare "gazelle", "elephant", etc).
*The plurals ''[[rhinoceri]]'' and ''[[rhinoceroi]]'' (formed by association with other Latin and Greek plurals) are generally considered erroneous or jocular.
*The Latin-derived plural form ''[[rhinocerotes]]'' is usually considered as a plural of the archaic form ''[[rhinocerot]]''.

